Mike,

That&#39;s a cool runner.  It looks like some of the features might be valuable
enhancements to the core runner.

However, I&#39;m not sure if this is what the original poster wanted.  What do
you think?

   David Saff

On 4/5/07, Mike Norman &lt;michael.norman@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;
&gt; --- In junit@yahoogroups.com, &quot;cliveborrageiro&quot; &lt;cliveborrageiro@...&gt;
&gt; wrote:
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Hi,
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; I&#39;m using a Parameterized test and would like to perform a single
&gt; &gt; setup state (like @BeforeClass) for all test methods to use. This
&gt; &gt; setup method needs to use the parameter passed into the constructor.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; The problem is that @BeforeClass needs to be static and is called
&gt; &gt; before the constructor, there I&#39;m unable to get the parameter for the
&gt; &gt; setup.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Any suggestions...
&gt; &gt; Thank you,
&gt; &gt; Clive
&gt; &gt;
&gt;
&gt; I have created a custom JUnit4 Runner:
&gt;
&gt; @RunWith(junit.extensions.pb4.ParameterizedBeforeRunner.class)
&gt;
&gt; Supports an optional parameter to be passed into static @BeforeClass
&gt; methods:
&gt;
&gt;   @BeforeClass
&gt;   public static void setUpBefore(Properties p) ...
&gt;
&gt; The rules are:
&gt;
&gt; If your test class is in a package com.foo.bar, then in your
&gt; classpath the directory com/foo/bar one can place a standard Java
&gt; .properties file. If your test class is called &#39;ASimpleTestSuite&#39;
&gt; then the file MUST be called &#39;asimpletestsuite.properties&#39;
&gt; (all-lower).
&gt;
&gt; The same Properties is passed to any @AfterClass with the
&gt; appropriate method signature. Regular JUnit4 @BeforeClass/@AfterClass
&gt; methods without the Properties argument still work.
&gt;
&gt; Additionally there is a System Property that is a global
&gt; merge/override:
&gt;
&gt; -
&gt; Djunit.extensions.parameterizedB4.properties={path_to}/override.properties
&gt;
&gt; any keys in override.properties will (obviously) override those same
&gt; keys from the testclass&#39; local &#39;XXX.properties&#39;; otherwise, the
&gt; operation is a merge of the 2 sets of Properties.
&gt;
&gt; I have made this runner work with the suite runner:
&gt;
&gt; @RunWith(ParameterizedBeforeRunner.class)
&gt; @SuiteClasses({
&gt;     ASimpleTestSuite.class,
&gt;     AnotherSimpleTestSuite.class
&gt; })
&gt;
&gt; Additional changes:
&gt; - added a state machine to standard test listeners so that the
&gt;    run report displayed at the end shows ACTUAL passed/ignored/failed
&gt;    counts
&gt; - added a &#39;-quiet&#39; flag: does the obvious, causes the run report
&gt;    to be suppressed
&gt; - added a &#39;-verbose&#39; flag: shows additional information as to
&gt;    exactly WHICH test passed/failed/or was ignored
&gt; - added a &#39;-stopTestsOnFailure&#39;: stop all testing upon detecting
&gt;    first failure
&gt; - in addition to the design-time @Ignore annotation, added a
&gt;    runtime COMPUTED ignore(String, boolean) method
&gt; - an Ant task &lt;ParameterizedBeforeJUnit4&gt; compiled against 1.6.5
&gt;    (ToDo - 1.7.0 version)
&gt;
&gt; With respect to licensing, it is likely that it will be released
&gt; under the EPL, perhaps as soon as the end of the month.
